## Technology Stack

### HTML (Structure)

HTML is used to create the basic structure of the Expense Tracker. It defines elements such as input fields, buttons, forms, tables, and sections where users can enter and view their expense details.

### CSS (Design)

CSS is responsible for the visual appearance of the application. It controls colors, fonts, layouts, spacing, and responsiveness, ensuring that the Expense Tracker looks clean and works properly on both desktop and mobile devices.

### JavaScript (Functionality)

JavaScript adds interactivity to the application. It handles user actions such as adding expenses, calculating total spending, filtering expenses by category, generating summaries, and updating information on the screen without reloading the page.

### Browser Local Storage (Data Storage)

Local Storage is used to save expense data directly in the user's browser. When a user adds an expense, the information is stored locally, allowing the data to remain available even after the browser is refreshed or reopened. This eliminates the need for a database in the initial version of the project.
